{\rtlch\af2\alang1025\afs24\ltrch\b0\i0\fs20\lang1033\langnp1033\langfe1033\langfenp1033\loch\af2\dbch\af2\hich\f2\strike0\ulnone\cf3 The employee, a switchman for the railroad, was injured when he fell as he attempted to step down in the dark to a place where a running board should have been but was not. He brought suit against his employer for his injuries, alleging violations of the Federal Safety Appliance Act, which required that all railway cars be equipped with secure running boards, and the Federal Employers' Liability Act. A jury returned a verdict for the employee. The trial court overruled the employer's motion for a new trial. The court affirmed the judgment, determining that under the evidence the employer was liable for compensatory damages for the employee's injuries. The jury had the duty to weigh the conflicting testimony of the expert witnesses regarding the employee's injuries that resulted from his fall. The trial court properly instructed the jury that they were to weigh and consider the expert opinions along with the other testimony in the case and give them such weight as they thought right under all the facts and circumstances. Damages were not excessive in light of the extent and permanency of the employee's disability, his inability to work, and the hopelessness of his condition.}
