\*\bkmkend Bookmark_para_27}{\*\bkmkstart Bookmark_I4G5SJRX0K1MNJ34T0000400_2}{\*\bkmkend Bookmark_I4G5SJRX0K1MNJ34T0000400_2}{\*\bkmkstart Bookmark_LNHNREFclscc4}{\*\bkmkend Bookmark_LNHNREFclscc4}{\rtlch\af2\alang1025\afs24\ltrch\b0\i0\fs20\lang1033\langnp1033\langfe1033\langfenp1033
\loch\af2\dbch\af2\hich\f2\strike0\ulnone\cf3 "The jury does not sit simply to register the opinion of an expert witness even if it be undisputed. It is its own exclusive function to pass upon the fact put in issue. The testimony of the expert may not be arbitrarily rejected, but, like the evidence of every other witness, it is to be considered by the jurors who are to accord to it influence, much or little, according as it appeals to their intelligent and impartial minds in view of all the facts and circumstances developed on the trial and the common knowledge and experience of mankind."}
{\rtlch\afs24\ltrch\fs24\par}\pard\plain\itap0\s0\fi0\sb200\sa0\aspalpha\aspnum\adjustright\ltrpar\li0\lin0\ri0\rin0\qj\faauto\sl260\slmult0\rtlch\afs24\ltrch\fs24{\*\bkmkstart Bookmark_para_28}{\*\bkmkend Bookmark_para_28}{\rtlch\af2\alang1025\afs24
\ltrch\b\i0\fs20\lang1033\langnp1033\langfe1033\langfenp1033\loch\af2\dbch\af2\hich\f2\strike0\ulnone\cf3 \~[*490]\~}{\rtlch\af2\alang1025\afs24\ltrch\b0\i0\fs20\lang1033\langnp1033\langfe1033\langfenp1033\loch\af2\dbch\af2\hich\f2\strike0\ulnone\cf3  }{
\rtlch\af2\alang1025\afs24\ltrch\b\i0\fs20\lang1033\langnp1033\langfe1033\langfenp1033\loch\af2\dbch\af2\hich\f2\strike0\ulnone\cf3 \~[**33]\~}{\rtlch\af2\alang1025\afs24\ltrch\b0\i0\fs20\lang1033\langnp1033\langfe1033\langfenp1033\loch\af2\dbch\af2\hich\f2\strike0
\ulnone\cf3  In Jones on Evidence, Vol. 2, sec. 392, it is said:}{\rtlch\afs24\ltrch\fs24\par}\pard\plain\itap0\s0\fi0\sb200\sa0\aspalpha\aspnum\adjustright\ltrpar\li400\lin400\ri0\rin0\qj\faauto\sl260\slmult0\rtlch\afs24\ltrch\fs24{\*\bkmkstart Bookmark_para_29}
{\*\bkmkend Bookmark_para_29}{\rtlch\af2\alang1025\afs24\ltrch\b0\i0\fs20\lang1033\langnp1033\langfe1033\langfenp1033\loch\af2\dbch\af2\hich\f2\strike0\ulnone\cf3 "When the testimony consists of mere inferences from assumed facts, of opinions against opinion, and especially of the opinions of those zealous witnesses who betray the bias of the advocate, it may be highly proper for the court to caution the jury against the dangers of such evidence. The cases already referred to sufficiently illustrate the rule that }
{\*\bkmkstart Bookmark_LNHNREFclscc5}{\*\bkmkend Bookmark_LNHNREFclscc5}{\rtlch\af2\alang1025\afs24\ltrch\b0\i0\fs20\lang1033\langnp1033\langfe1033\langfenp1033\loch\af2\dbch\af2\hich\f2\strike0\ulnone\cf3 the jury must, in passing upon expert testimony, like other testimony, finally determine the degree of weight to which, under all the circumstances, it is entitled. It is for the jury to estimate the value of the opinion and accept or reject it; it is for them to find the facts on which it is based, true or untrue; they are to regard the opinion simply as a sort of super structure imposed upon a hypothetical foundation, which stands or falls with its supporting facts.--In the light of an aid to the jury, expert testimony is assuredly valuable. The opinions of experts, unchallenged and established in the mind of the jury by proof of the constituent facts, are entitled to consideration the same as other evidence which has gone to the jury. Nevertheless, when the jury are told that}
{\rtlch\af2\alang1025\afs24\ltrch\b\i0\fs20\lang1033\langnp1033\langfe1033\langfenp1033\loch\af2\dbch\af2\hich\f2\strike0\ulnone\cf3 \~[**34]\~}{\rtlch\af2\alang1025\afs24\ltrch\b0\i0\fs20\lang1033\langnp1033\langfe1033\langfenp1033\loch\af2\dbch\af2
\hich\f2\strike0\ulnone\cf3  the expert evidence is advisory only, and not binding on them, that they are not to surrender their own convictions but they should accord to such evidence such weight as they believe from all the facts and circumstances in evidence the same are entitled to receive, full justice has been accorded to the class of testimony we are dealing with.'}
{\rtlch\afs24\ltrch\fs24\par}\pard\plain\itap0\s0\fi0\sb200\sa0\aspalpha\aspnum\adjustright\ltrpar\li0\lin0\ri0\rin0\qj\faauto\sl260\slmult0\rtlch\afs24\ltrch\fs24{\*\bkmkstart Bookmark_para_30}{\*\bkmkend Bookmark_para_30}{\rtlch\af2\alang1025\afs24
\ltrch\b0\i0\fs20\lang1033\langnp1033\langfe1033\langfenp1033\loch\af2\dbch\af2\hich\f2\strike0\ulnone\cf3 In Wigmore on Evidence, Vol. 3, sec. 1917, the learned author summarizes his historical discussion of opinion evidence by showing that the ground of the old objection to such evidence lay in view of "mere opinion" as a guess, and belief without good grounds; but that in the modern sense "opinion" is an inference from observed and communicable data. The opinions given by the witnesses in this }
{\rtlch\af2\alang1025\afs24\ltrch\b0\i0\fs20\lang1033\langnp1033\langfe1033\langfenp1033\loch\af2\dbch\af2\hich\f2\strike0\ulnone\cf3 cause}{\rtlch\af2\alang1025\afs24\ltrch\b0\i0\fs20\lang1033\langnp1033\langfe1033\langfenp1033\loch\af2\dbch\af2\hich\f2\strike0
\ulnone\cf3  are not mere opinions or guesses but they are inferences from observed and communicable data.}{\rtlch\afs24\ltrch\fs24\par}\pard\plain\itap0\s0\fi0\sb200\sa0\aspalpha\aspnum\adjustright\ltrpar\li0\lin0\ri0\rin0\qj\faauto\sl260\slmult0\rtlch\afs24
\ltrch\fs24{\*\bkmkstart Bookmark_para_31}{\*\bkmkend Bookmark_para_31}{\rtlch\af2\alang1025\afs24\ltrch\b0\i0\fs20\lang1033\langnp1033\langfe1033\langfenp1033\loch\af2\dbch\af2\hich\f2\strike0\ulnone\cf3 The rules above quoted do not seem to be contrary to the valuations of opinion evidence disclosed in our Tennessee decisions upon that subject.}
